1
00:00:05,685 --> 00:00:08,227
“The boast of heraldry,
the pomp of pow’r,
 

2
00:00:08,227 --> 00:00:10,404
And all that beauty,
all that wealth e’er gave

3
00:00:10,404 --> 00:00:12,319
Awaits alike the inevitable hour;
 

4
00:00:12,319 --> 00:00:15,962
The paths of glory
lead but to the grave.”
 

5
00:00:15,962 --> 00:00:17,769
Gray's Elegy.

6
00:00:17,769 --> 00:00:20,998
Memento mori | Enlightenment

7
00:00:21,443 --> 00:00:23,681
After he wrote that, he was

8
00:00:23,681 --> 00:00:25,796
—still he's a minor poet,

9
00:00:25,796 --> 00:00:29,056
but then he was really an unknown…

10
00:00:29,056 --> 00:00:32,386
but after he wrote this poem
they published it in some newspapers,

11
00:00:32,424 --> 00:00:37,303
he remarked, he said, “I woke up
one morning and I was famous.”

12
00:00:38,258 --> 00:00:41,239
However high you go,

13
00:00:41,239 --> 00:00:45,498
ā-brahma-bhuvanāl lokāḥ
punar āvartino 'rjuna 
[Bg: 8.16],

14
00:00:45,498 --> 00:00:50,902
it all ends up in the same place:
the grave.

15
00:00:52,711 --> 00:00:56,065
It's all finished at that time.

16
00:00:56,811 --> 00:01:01,344
That's not a morbid thought,
it's called “memento mori”:

17
00:01:01,344 --> 00:01:09,377
things that remind us
—death reminders—are enlightening,

18
00:01:09,377 --> 00:01:13,148
because that's the situation
that we're in.

19
00:01:13,148 --> 00:01:22,599
Every day, the news…
death is front page news.

20
00:01:22,967 --> 00:01:28,408
The famous die, the wealthy die,
the rich die,

21
00:01:28,408 --> 00:01:34,233
the beautiful die, the young die.

22
00:01:35,598 --> 00:01:40,615
Dealing with the mortality issue

23
00:01:40,615 --> 00:01:48,550
is not cowardly;
it requires some courage.

24
00:01:48,596 --> 00:01:53,286
When someone get's cancer in America,
especially a famous person,

25
00:01:53,362 --> 00:01:56,669
they all—some representative,
a friend, someone—will come

26
00:01:56,669 --> 00:02:02,302
and go, “Bill's a real fighter,
he's gonna fight this thing.”

27
00:02:02,671 --> 00:02:04,831
You know there's a place
in Ireland

28
00:02:04,831 --> 00:02:09,026
where they'll accept a bet
on just about anything…

29
00:02:09,290 --> 00:02:12,049
I'm betting on cancer.

30
00:02:12,223 --> 00:02:16,962
Anyone wants to take m—,
I'll bet, I'll always bet, on cancer.

31
00:02:16,962 --> 00:02:21,987
“He's gonna fight this thing”…
and he's gonna lose.

32
00:02:21,987 --> 00:02:26,265
So the great atheist Christopher Hitchens,
he died last year.

33
00:02:26,465 --> 00:02:28,917
Even he mocked this stuff,
he said,

34
00:02:28,917 --> 00:02:34,026
“It's as if to say,“
if they write in the obituary,

35
00:02:34,026 --> 00:02:40,744
“'After a long struggle with mortality,
he succumbed.’”

36
00:02:41,155 --> 00:02:47,238
Death is an inevitability
for everyone,

37
00:02:48,272 --> 00:02:53,984
so, before another death occurs…

38
00:02:53,984 --> 00:02:56,770
that's what it says.

39
00:02:59,745 --> 00:03:02,250
Tasyaiva hetoḥ prayateta kovido

40
00:03:02,250 --> 00:03:08,544
na labhyate yad bhramatām
upary adhaḥ 
[SB: 1.5.18],

41
00:03:10,344 --> 00:03:15,398
in many places, the Bhāgavatam's
imploring us:

42
00:03:15,398 --> 00:03:20,098
while you have this
opportunity before you,

43
00:03:20,098 --> 00:03:25,472
dharmaḥ svanuṣṭhitaḥ puṁsāṁ
viṣvaksena-kathāsu yaḥ

44
00:03:25,472 --> 00:03:29,380
notpādayed yadi ratiṁ
śrama eva hi kevalam 
[SB: 1.2.8].

45
00:03:29,380 --> 00:03:31,944
Even to devotees it's saying,

46
00:03:31,944 --> 00:03:35,810
if the end result
of whatever it is you're doing

47
00:03:35,810 --> 00:03:42,271
is not increased attraction
for hearing and chanting about Kṛṣṇa,

48
00:03:42,271 --> 00:03:46,040
you're wasting your time.

49
00:03:46,605 --> 00:03:50,565
In another place:
kāmasya nendriya-prītir

50
00:03:50,572 --> 00:03:55,087
lābho jīveta yāvatā
jīvasya tattva-jijñāsā

51
00:03:55,087 --> 00:03:57,352
nārtho yaś ceha karmabhiḥ
[SB: 1.2.10];

52
00:03:57,352 --> 00:04:01,801
a formula is given, how to balance
the mundane and the spiritual,

53
00:04:01,801 --> 00:04:03,424
and what is being said?

54
00:04:03,424 --> 00:04:06,445
You only need to accumulate 
the mundane

55
00:04:06,445 --> 00:04:09,751
to the point where
it allows you to engage

56
00:04:09,751 --> 00:04:14,345
maximum energy in spiritual culture.

57
00:04:14,345 --> 00:04:17,101
That's the right balance,
that's the right formula.

58
00:04:17,101 --> 00:04:18,855
Otherwise it's just to be ignorant.

59
00:04:18,855 --> 00:04:21,942
I've seen goats in Kolkata,

60
00:04:21,942 --> 00:04:24,793
they're on their way
to the slaughterhouse,

61
00:04:24,793 --> 00:04:27,206
and how you know…

62
00:04:27,206 --> 00:04:31,651
they put red paint on the neck.

63
00:04:32,204 --> 00:04:33,860
And the guy's herding them over,

64
00:04:33,860 --> 00:04:36,934
then they get into the line
and you'll see:

65
00:04:36,934 --> 00:04:40,255
while they're waiting
to get their heads chopped off,

66
00:04:40,255 --> 00:04:43,244
a male goat mounting a she-goat

67
00:04:43,244 --> 00:04:45,595
and having sex with the she-goat—

68
00:04:45,595 --> 00:04:50,454
he's gonna have his head
cut off in three minutes.

69
00:04:56,113 --> 00:05:01,380
Hello?
H-h-h-h-h-h-hello?

70
00:05:02,468 --> 00:05:05,981
“The Lord is my shepherd,
I shall not wa-a-a-ant.”

71
00:05:08,456 --> 00:05:12,512
Have to be forward; look.

72
00:05:12,512 --> 00:05:16,557
Mṛtyuḥ sarva-haraś cāham
[Bg: 10.34]:

73
00:05:16,557 --> 00:05:20,879
Kṛṣṇa says, “If you don't
get it any other way,

74
00:05:20,879 --> 00:05:24,494
mṛtyuḥ sarva-haraś cāham,
I come before you as death

75
00:05:24,494 --> 00:05:28,232
and take away everything.”

76
00:05:28,326 --> 00:05:31,923
When my brother, who was
a theist when he was younger,

77
00:05:31,923 --> 00:05:34,526
wanted to be a priest,

78
00:05:34,526 --> 00:05:38,481
then got “educated”
by enlightenment teachers

79
00:05:38,481 --> 00:05:42,138
and became an atheist
and then a doctor and everything

80
00:05:42,138 --> 00:05:45,108
—I could say this
if he was in the room.

81
00:05:45,108 --> 00:05:53,898
Anyway… he's a surgeon,
big time neurologist,

82
00:05:53,898 --> 00:05:57,174
but when he was 37
he went in to operate one day

83
00:05:57,174 --> 00:05:59,993
and he keeled over
onto the operating table

84
00:05:59,993 --> 00:06:03,177
and they had to operate on him,

85
00:06:03,177 --> 00:06:07,583
he had an attack
of gastroenteritis or something.

86
00:06:07,583 --> 00:06:10,422
And so it looked like
he was gonna die—

87
00:06:10,422 --> 00:06:14,548
the doctors weren't telling us,
they thought,

88
00:06:14,548 --> 00:06:18,791
“Prepare yourselves
that he's going to die.”

89
00:06:18,923 --> 00:06:25,521
And our family's
noted for the sense of humour…

90
00:06:26,874 --> 00:06:30,659
Anyway, so I went to see him
and I opened the door

91
00:06:30,659 --> 00:06:35,762
and I said, “I heard
you called for a priest”,

92
00:06:35,762 --> 00:06:38,063
but he wasn't laughing at the time,

93
00:06:38,063 --> 00:06:43,897
and he turned to me and he went,
“It's God! It's God!”

94
00:06:43,897 --> 00:06:47,802
Not that I was God,
but what he meant was,

95
00:06:47,802 --> 00:06:50,511
“What happened to me, it's God!”

96
00:06:50,511 --> 00:06:54,401
And he said, for those who don't
get it any other way,

97
00:06:54,401 --> 00:06:57,451
he got it momentarily.

98
00:06:57,451 --> 00:07:01,601
But then he recovered,
gradually, gradually,

99
00:07:01,601 --> 00:07:07,127
and then resumed his position
as an atheist—a so-called atheist.

100
00:07:09,396 --> 00:07:16,360
I think he's a closet theist,
a Kṛṣṇa-ite at heart,

101
00:07:17,608 --> 00:07:23,216
and he's counting on me,
he's betting on me.

102
00:07:25,976 --> 00:07:29,034
He does pay attention.

